key_facts: AI Engineer is responsible for turning AI models from ideas into real-world systems.
Deep learning is not the only choice, traditional machine learning algorithms can be more effective in certain scenarios.
Understanding business problems and data quality are crucial steps in starting an AI project.
AI Engineers work closely with Product Managers, Data Engineers, Backend Engineers, DevOps or Cloud Engineers.
Data issues like dirty, incomplete, or time-varying data pose challenges for AI Engineers.
Monitoring models after deployment is essential to detect errors and performance degradation.
Knowledge of cloud platforms is beneficial for AI Engineers, especially AWS, Azure, and Google Cloud.
Handling large-scale data requires understanding distributed processing concepts.
AI Engineers need to consider ethical issues such as bias and privacy in their work.
Common mistakes include overfitting on complex models and neglecting deployment, monitoring, and maintenance.
Leveraging both theoretical knowledge and practical experience is ideal for learning AI Engineering.
Career progression includes roles like Senior AI Engineer, AI Architect, Head of AI, or moving into management.
Key mathematical foundations are probability & statistics, linear algebra, and optimization.
